The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", as published in a brochure
Women considered as witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually older, cannot work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "return" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men seldom suffer such but."
“Nor are healthy young women isolated, because they help in the work and have children,” explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, is occupied in a special residence of more than one hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual “social measure.”
He issued an informative brochure that should help prevent witch hunting.
However, this has a hit.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso can’t read,” warns Die Standard newspaper of the disadvantages of written awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, Burkina Faso’s neighbor, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate cluster of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman was caught in the oil that is used for ritual anointings.
It was set on fire when the group wanted to "expel evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The Der Standard newspaper quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: “The devourers of human souls have always posed a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government tries to appease the witch hunt, in the Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
“Gambian President Jammeh, after his aunt’s death, launched an extensive hunt for witches who had allegedly been linked to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself through black magic.”
“To help him, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president’s personal escort, forcibly took randomly chosen men and women from Gambian peoples to the president’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
At the farm, the arrested people had to drink a herbal potion with hallucinogenic effects that also caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive the stay on the estate.
After international pressure, about 1,000 people were finally released.
Bakala tenant: warms up with coal stoves and signs higher rent
The elderly and reluctant man walked through the doors of the RPG Byty customer service center of the "coal magnate" Zde<0xC5><0x88>ek Bakala, the largest private owner of flats for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried documents with the new three-story rental contracts: his, his daughter’s and his son’s, who is serving sentence.
All three have just caught the rent liberalization.
Instead of 3,500 CZK per month, the child will pay 4,100 CZK from next year onwards for a two-room apartment with separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in the new contract of his son, over whose signature he has full powers.
“But I signed it,” he explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing on how to proceed in these cases.
But before this, man only makes a move.
“Every one says one thing,” he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a major testing laboratory for liberalization.
After New Year will happen with the vast majority of flats that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
That is why Aktuáln<0xC4><0x9B>.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and, by Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a number pickup machine.
"Rental 2011", can be read on a light button of your touch screen.
When you press it, a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
There is almost no time to read "157" and the number already appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an elderly couple arrives to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, such as formerly: requests for settlements, insurance issues, and the like.
Letters with the new leases will arrive in Ostrava to the tenants’ mailboxes of most of the 44,000 RPG-owned flats around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes to them in the cards an increase of the rent between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window in the customer service center for new rentals opens.
"It's been running for a week, so it's starting," the workers who are in it respond after a brief hesitation when the client introduces himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and the former apartments for miners in Bakala are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, the Vice-President of the Parliament, originally from Ostrava, Lubom<0xC3><0xAD>r Zaorálek, of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSD, has already dealt with them loud and clear, and they now appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
“I wasn’t even changed the damn bathroom dish,” the man mentioned in the introduction vents out.
According to the workers, at the moment they are mostly retired to check if they receive a discount on the rent if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15 will also receive half of the discount on the February rental.
However, the window of mining “liberalization” certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
“Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only about forty or fifty people asked for the rental in 2011,” she said.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its planks to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rent, the matter must be resolved by an independent judge.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only possible and fully lawful way to proceed," RPG said in a statement.
“No one is going to be judged here,” says one of Byty’s RPG employees and a man standing on the street in front of the customer service center gives him, at least in part, the reason.
“I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I don’t have the means to go to court,” he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
“Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait,” he says.
The rent regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic in early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
"The current rents still do not even cover the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund," recalls Pavel Klime<0xC5><0xA1>, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, who adds that the neglected state of the community fund that annoys the tenants is, for the owners, the main reason for increasing the rent.
While during the five years that elapsed between 2005 and 2010 RPG could with the rents invest in apartments four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the waiting room seats, now repeats some data that highlights in red.
“The rent increase in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties.”
"In addition, it will always be a maximum of 7.50 CZK per square meter per month," it says on the screen.
Only increased by 38% the 400-story rental of the RPG portfolio.
“In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts, of 19.66 crowns per square meter,” RPG says.
On 2,600 flats, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that the liberalization will not affect rents at once, but will escalate between four to eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent increase (see the graph) back into the floors, mainly in heating savings: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to people signing the rent increase agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need daycare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
Nobody would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with all its own to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can come to it.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio numerous well-known buildings in Brno emerged, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-garden.
Around 90 people work in the company, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, daycare is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers its workers as part of its social program.
The builders and architects thus have the possibility of combining a demanding profession with the care of their children.
The mini-garden was an idea of the employees of Arch.Designu themselves and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company’s mini-garden is financed through the European Social Fund under the Human Resources and Employment Operational Programme, as well as the Czech Republic’s state budget.
Thanks to the funding granted (a grant of more than CZK 2.8 million) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified personnel and services.
When funding is exhausted (two years), the Arch.Design company is obliged to keep the mini-garden running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and in the submission of the application for funding contributed the company Economy Rating.
The care of the children is in the hands of qualified staff, and a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The kindergarten currently hosts children without age limit, although most of them are less than three years old.
Since it is a "mini-garden", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to suit the needs of the parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is a teaching and individual care, the contents of the mini-care programme are comparable to the usual pre-school programme.
In it, children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach to English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up school children late when they are away from their workplace.
Parents are more productive when they work.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the signing companies that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program strengthened the marketing of staff.
The House of Bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Observe the interiors of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur, and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Because of its skeleton-like shape, locals nicknamed it "the house of bones."
Its organic shapes, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade reminiscent of scales and the ubiquitous gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
The cover of the house plays with dream lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, we observe a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought out order.
At night, the entire facade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Snake and the twisting of the shapes continues to surprise us also inside.
The corrugated wood copies the frames of the windows, the railings, the ornaments of the doors, the gazebos and the signs.
Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the bustling shopping street of Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA0>cia, emerged from the refurbishment of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of various apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> alone.
The architect Josep Mar<0xC3><0xAD>a Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his plans of the project appeared ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade.
In the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s Güell Park, in which other pieces of it are found.
Due to its organic form, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones" shortly after its completion.
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it "the house of yawning".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, appears the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motifs.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed in the house a unique system for the time of central heating with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Its forty-five-degree inclination may be strange.
During the construction, Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> did not respect the building rules of the time at all and did not allow himself to be influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so shocked by the result that it asked to be corrected.
He was annoyed, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
Arrangements were never made, on the contrary: just fifteen days after the city council’s request, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors was installed the owner himself.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely traversed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the living rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without having to give up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s reconstruction, not only got a new fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> plays with light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and skylights.
The play with the two colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb the rays of the sun.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage list.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most recharged apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and expanded the visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, reaching 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of entry of other Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> constructions into the city.
