Many people were afraid of the case of the missing Ani<0xC4><0x8D>ka and began to report on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the expense of invading your privacy.
“We all try to tell ourselves that it’s not about spying, but about another way to decrease the chances of a tragedy,” says Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, one of the providers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they get into someone's bag without their knowledge, but we have not yet come across such cases."
“Most customers actually buy it for safety reasons,” Pilin adds.
In his opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bo<0xC4><0x8D>ková warns about the fact that if the child does not want to carry it, he will simply throw it away.
“Even the youngest children show great creativity when it comes to intentionally losing certain things if they want to prevent them from being controlled.”
“In the past, parents had a lot of confidence in mobile phones, but they could be turned off as easily as the tracking device,” Bo<0xC4><0x8D>ková says.
In his opinion, it is debatable whether in case of attack such a device is really useful.
“If it is a prepared kidnapping, the perpetrator will almost always check whether the child is carrying any kind of electronic device that can reveal their location.”
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices is spreading, it will also look for them, since their sale will undoubtedly be made with a lot of advertising."
“In such cases, criminals always go one step ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the case of an impromptu attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert <0xC4><0x8C>ech of the company RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is immediately destroyed, its presence can help.
“The device can be configured to send the position regularly after a certain period.”
“If you suffer damage, it will at least facilitate the last position of the person in question.”
“The more expensive devices have a built-in tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and stands still, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question,” says <0xC4><0x8C>ech.
In his opinion, such a service can be obtained even with smartphones with navigation, in which only special software should be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment they are devices with a similar size to a match box or smaller mobile phones.
Therefore, they can be lost.
According to Pilin de Macro Weil, for that reason, tests are currently being conducted with devices that look like a digital clock.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential attacker may not identify the device."
“Or I identify him after a certain amount of time, which can save the police time,” he adds.
Even if the tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hanging, they will still use the same technology that is used for vehicle tracking.
This is the position check with a GPS system (used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough wicks to encircle the whole Czech Republic, but they only last two years.
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of wick to detonate explosives.
Last year, the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of wick to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the service life of the wick is two years, four at most.
The army bought the wick for explosives from the STV Group, a.s. for forty million crowns.
The General's staff responded to MF DNES justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of wick by saying that soldiers need 60 kilometers of wick a year for training maneuvers.
According to the calculations of the pyrotechnics of the army, with which MF DNES was contacted, it is decided, however, that in such a case, such maneuvers should be carried out with frequent use of explosives every year also all generals, high command officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
Neither Defence Minister Alexandr Vondr nor Army Captain Vlastimil Picek were exempt.
Only then could it be justified for the army to spend sixty kilometers of wick.
Such a length is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if it were, the army would have sufficient stocks for more than ten years.
If, on the contrary, as experts say, for the initial training of each new professional arrives with a maximum of two meters of wick, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the rapid-intervention brigade recently complained personally to Minister Vondra because they say they barely have ammunition for various weapons, so even the practice of shooting for money is limited.
And let’s not talk about the lack of underwear.
"I also don't get to understand that we are repeatedly bought such amounts of wick."
“But it’s their decision and they’ll undoubtedly know why they act like that.”
“For us, the army is a good customer that we as a company try to satisfy,” admitted Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>ck<0xC3><0xBD>, commercial director of STV Group.
Ministry of Defense spokesman Jan Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek defends the hundreds of kilometers of wick, saying he will also have stocks of this "munition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>ck<0xC3><0xBD> of STV Group indicates that the wick has a shelf life of only four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or the police, of two years.
"If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four," says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its useful life, each ammunition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm the soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require an additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of wick, it got a discount.
“They cost us 60 percent less than last year’s order of 244 kilometers,” said spokesman Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek of the Ministry of Defence’s shopping centre.
Just to compare: the annual wick consumption of police pyrotechnics, which eliminate munitions from World War II or left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask only the right amount to deplete the ammunition before its useful life runs out.
This was decided for safety reasons for the pyrotechnics and, in the meantime, more modern and reliable types of wick can be obtained.
The Ministry already has clear difficulties in finishing tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the time of the Warsaw Pact, when the Czechoslovak army of 200,000 people was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnics with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years there will be the following problem with the current one: we will have to eliminate hundreds of kilometers of old wick, which is now being bought "cheap".
