Families will have to pay an additional cost of several hundred crowns per month
Since January, households will have to pay not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, higher rents.
As a result, families will have to take several hundred crowns more out of their wallet from January onwards than they do now.
The price of electricity increases by 4.6%, gas by around 2%, in some cities they will have to pay up to 10% more for the water supply and many also increase the price of central heating.
The increase in electricity for families living in apartments should amount to about 100 more crowns a year than now.
However, major electricity suppliers have lowered prices, as support for energy production from renewable sources, in particular photovoltaics, has increased.
However, gas is moderately expensive, especially at a time when heating is most used and therefore higher consumption.
In this case, they must also have a couple of hundred more crowns a year.
While electricity and gas are priced across the country, the price change for central heating varies from place to place.
The increase in prices is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay an additional 50 kroner per month for central heating from January, while families in Liberec will pay an additional 1,000 kroner per year.
Prague residents will also have to endure a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially if the city increases the rent of infrastructure.
If the rent does not change, the people of Prague will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will remain among the lowest in the whole country.
In northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will rise by 7.4%.
They can significantly increase the rental prices of 450,000 rented flats in Prague, where the regulation will end in January.
For example, CPI Byty, which owns around 2,500 flats in <0xC3><0x9A>st<0xC3><0xAD> nad Labem, will increase rent from January by up to 100%.
The company will take to the courts those who do not agree with the new rent.
Regulated rents, which benefit residents of around 300,000 flats, could increase by as much as 10% next year.
Czech young people get drunk with Fernet and rum. The beer is no longer in mode, because it takes effect slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause young drinkers under the age of fifteen to end up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome the hangover are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors encountering such cases in the hospital’s pediatric admissions.
“Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because it takes a long time to get drunk.”
"Now the trend is strong alcoholic beverages," says Pravo, the head of pediatrics at Ho<0xC5><0x99>ovice Hospital in central Bohemia, Lud<0xC4><0x9B>k Pelikán.
"When they manage to get a bottle from their father's cupboard, it may be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
“Vodka has the advantage that it lightens with juice and doesn’t smell as much,” he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokeswoman of Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
"Normally, it's usually Fernet or rum."
"Those are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren."
"In some cases, they use brandy that they picked up at home," adds Jurinová.
According to Chief Pelikán, they are 13 and 14-year-old drinkers who usually appear in hospitals.
Prior to Ho<0xC5><0x99>ovice, where he has worked since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances were taking young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to enter maybe four times."
"It started at the age of twelve, when she was brought in with 3.5 alcohol in her blood, plus a mixture of ecstasy," the department's doctor said.
"He was at the Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice fair at some dance party."
“The interesting thing is that his mother wasn’t even surprised that his daughter disappeared for 48 hours,” the boss is surprised.
It is precisely the lack of interest of parents or even their clear tolerance for drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, one cannot speak properly of dependence.
"Alcoholic is understood to mean a person who has had a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children."
“In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is more due to a systematically failed social or family environment,” Chief Pelikan explains.
According to the spokeswoman Jurinová, this year at the pediatric clinic of Motol 40 drunken children were hospitalized until mid-November.
However, the statistics show only those who come with severe intoxication and must remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after the walking medical examination, go home with their parents or with the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases where children simply gather after school and drink brandy, for Pelikán there are three seasonal ups and downs to mention: Witch’s Day, New Year’s Day and the end of the school year.
“In such a circumstance, they drink for poor grades or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holiday.”
"On Witch's Day, I've seen up to seven drunken children in admissions at a time," Pelikan said.
Drinkers who spend the night in detox under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided by injecting a serum with glucose and the nutrients that the body lacks.
"These do it much better, because after the hectic night, they get up well and they don't hurt anything."
“They are only confused about where they are,” Pelikán says, adding that patients often lose good mood at least when they see the expenses they have generated.
The transfer by ambulance and hospitalization in a room for serious patients can cost tens of thousands of crowns.
“I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when on the visit I tell them directly to the children how much it has cost their drunkenness and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a job for young people to make enough money to pay for themselves that night,” Pelikán adds.
Health insurance, in his opinion perhaps as a regressive measure, which usually reimburses people for the costs of treatment, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
