He wanted the female members of chengguan, China’s voluminous urban order policemen, feared and despised for their capricious energetic measures and inclination to violence, to convey a certain impression to a handful of spectators.
"Firms!"
"Attention!"
Show them, he whispered, "How pretty girls are!"
Four girls who barely spent their teens wearing white gloves and identical olive green jackets and tight pants for attention.
Four pairs of black shoes perfectly aligned.
Four elegant hats perfectly placed above the hair tied with blue and white striped bows.
“Personally, I think they look normal,” Mr. Tang said, contemptuously.
"The models are beautiful."
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China’s urban inspectors.
One city ordered all new recruits to have a degree.
Guangdong Province changed the grayish-green color of the uniforms to a purportedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating gazes: in 2009, according to a report, 50 officers surrounded a disco of snack carts, and watched it constantly frowned for half an hour, until the street vendor picked up his stuff and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 inhabitants in Chengdu, has chosen a radical makeover.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police force, specifically chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the coarse police a softer, feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China’s diminutive respect for these city squads.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are only authorized to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese news media routinely portray a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei Province beat a passerby to death after using his cell phone to film them while dissolving a protest against a landfill.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors was stolen and published on the internet, describing how to effectively whip criminals without causing them to bleed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon street vendor suffered brain damage after a quarrel with five officers.
A video game full of violence, available for download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
“Chengguan has left a scar on the government,” lamented China Daily, a national publication, last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper called for “a really meticulous cleanup.”
Skeptics say the current approach is far from this.
After the district requested through a notice eight new female recruits in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News wondered if women had real duties or were simply a scenic distraction.
