For years, the U.S. government had been trying to persuade Belarus to give up its highly enriched uranium and appeared to have reached a point of no return last spring.
But U.S. officials told the Washington Post that a pair of classified operations were conducted with Belarus in the past two months, to remove 84.82 kg of weapons-qualified uranium from a Belarusian research facility.
This paved the way for Wednesday's deal to remove the rest of the material, about 227 kg, according to an official, who spoke from anonymity because of the confidentiality of the matter.
The deal appeared to be one of the most important outcomes of the 47-nation Nuclear Security Summit chaired by Obama in April, which excluded Belarus.
And apparently it was a good achievement to secure the invitation of the former Soviet Republic to the next summit in 2012.
“I was really fascinated by the fact that they wanted a place at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit.”
“This shows that this process is working,” said Ken Luongo, president of the Society for Global Security, a group that promotes nuclear security.
Clinton said the deal was "a very significant and important step" taken by Belarus.
In April 2009, Obama vowed in Prague to protect all vulnerable nuclear material worldwide over the next four years.
Since then, the U.S. government has helped six countries get rid of all their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries did so under the administration of George W. Bush.
At the time of Obama’s Nuclear Security Summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko had declared that the nation would never give up its uranium.
“We have conserved highly enriched uranium (hundreds of kilograms of what is basically weapons-qualified uranium) and low-enriched uranium,” Lukashenko said at the time.
"This is our raw material ... we are not going to make dirty bombs, and we are not going to sell them to anyone."
“We use it for research purposes, that’s all.”
However, Belarus approached the United States a few months ago, indicating interest in reaching an agreement.
Officials said the first task of removing uranium from Belarus in October was particularly complicated, as the material had been lightly irradiated.
Officials said it was loaded on a special train that traveled more than 2,000 km to a Russian facility for storage and disposal.
According to officials, the second operation ended on Monday and was carried out by plane.
The U.S. government spent $13 million on the tasks, and most of the money was used to supply Belarus with the installation of low-enriched uranium research, which is not suitable for nuclear weapons.
Andrew Bieniawski, an official with the Department of Energy working on Global Threat Reduction, said that “this was coordinated and orchestrated very carefully to strengthen trust” that led to the agreement signed by Clinton.
The James Martin Center for Nonproliferation Studies estimated this year that Belarus possessed at least 40 kilograms of weapons-grade uranium, as well as hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will try to eliminate its reservation by 2012, according to the joint statement.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly due to Lukashenko’s harsh crackdown on human rights.
But Wednesday’s statement suggested a potential detente.
“While progress on these global security issues is welcomed, the United States and Belarus recognized that greater respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus remains a central theme for improving bilateral relations, and is essential for the progress of the country and its citizens.”
