Go ahead that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another turning point in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of many of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the currency zone.
The second is the recovery of the framework, even if it now looks like science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigour, fines to transgressing countries, possible suspensions of payments of some of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defining for a long time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were spurring deficits, the German government pulled a constitutional reform off its sleeve to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be done (plans for fiscal rigour and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second on the forehead was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully extended the decision to save Greece.
Already then it was the object of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and published opinion were very much against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again emerges with a clear position, demanding the reform of the EU treaties, to make it possible to save a country while at the same time forcing private lenders to run for part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But its proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should attend the process of reform of the Union that makes these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, even though we now have to take measures with which he perhaps does not agree very much, from that date the old operation of the euro will have ended.
2013 will mark the birth of a new monetary area, in which violating countries will be severely sanctioned, may be forced to declare themselves in suspension of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also bear part of the cost.
Germany is pointing out to us that we must follow a severe path of growth with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, such as the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, is simply not going to tolerate it.
The envoy is clear.
And it would be wrong not to understand it.
It’s not just about bringing the government deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What they demand of us is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give way to greater peace of mind.
And that we take advantage of the window of opportunity they have given us, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood it this way and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with big companies and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite criticism of Merkel, the thesis that order must be put at home has made its way.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and it doesn’t look like they’re going to move it.
And, among the possibilities that are contemplated, that of leaving a currency zone too crowded with unreasonable countries, cannot be excluded.
Then Germany will always be able to tell us that it had already warned us.
Sport and Law Fraud
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos to Ajax show ingenuity but no willingness to escape a sanction.
The expulsion allegedly caused by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match played on 23 November against Ajax in the Champions League has caused ink to be written about whether such behavior is unsportsmanlike and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, short of a few minutes to finish the match (which their team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time to make fouls to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will already end up as leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next match of the league, against Auxerre, and can pass clean cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA Discipline Committee has sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two matches, and with different economic amounts to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the rules not written, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the case is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and that on past occasions has fined its players for similar acts) and the orchestrated dramatization, apparently by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history of histrionic technician and provocateur.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions commit fraud by law; because, in fact, they are actions respectful of the sports regulation, but they seem to circumvent their meaning.
The question is to examine the kind of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that comprises the sporting spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these assets that is alluded to by fair play is to prevent the team of the offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which did not happen either.
However, the paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it did not accommodate what we normally characterize as cheating or fraud of the law, because his violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely his action tried to be the most obvious to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the punishment.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders gain in the intentional misconduct examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that you do not put the opponent in a disadvantageous position or make a profit in the same game, because obviously the result of the action means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next game, as the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But it is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team can be eliminated at the first exchange, and also with this performance the players meet a penalty game and move on to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension by accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, from passing rounds, it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the sporting spirit, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favor to get the most out of what the rules allow.
In the present case, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without circumventing the punishment or running away from it.
Although the boundary between ingenuity and law fraud is blurred, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it was about two self-evictions and because of the way in which the transmission of the directive to provoke them took place.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
