I change the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must go to Visa Applicant Service Centers prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and as well as the waiting time.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedure for processing a visa at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to Visa Applicant Service (ASC) centers prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
ASC staff will take the applicant’s biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another one more for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a one-time payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for petition visa cases (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for merchant and investor visas.
Persons wishing to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Because the biometric information will be taken from the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in this shorter time than in the past.
Similarly, those applying for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For additional information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bulletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
