Avengers hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks issue has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous to the hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level and envisages a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of which nation it belongs to) is made up exclusively of press cuts.
The “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual customs only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except Berlusconi’s) and Gaddafi’s sinisterly ridiculous profile has long been giving cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret files should only be made up of public-knowledge news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you visit a bookstore dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Ch<0xC3><0xA2>teau, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to the occult not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown’s success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little eagerness) the head of the secret services (if he could not be, I know what, editor of the Libération), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the U.S. embassy in Rome to the State Department was the same as the Newsweek published the week before.
Then why have the revelations of these records caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that embassies, at least since World War II and since the Heads of State can call or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited exercises of representation, have become centers of espionage.
Any viewer who sees research films knows it perfectly, we just pretend we don’t know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker can search for the most secret secrets of the world’s most powerful country greatly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "banners".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in Orwell’s time, one could think of himself as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true ever since, being able to control every move thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer hold its own secrets be endured?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public realm; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that the secrets of Hillary Clinton were empty secrets means to take away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it has done a lot to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any reserved information on the net, since it would be like posting it on a poster in the middle of the street.
But it’s also clear that with today’s technologies, you can’t expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a Head of State has travelled by plane and contacted one of the counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my foresight is a thing of science fiction and, therefore, novelism, but I imagine government agents who travel discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned by memory or, at most, hiding some data written in the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept, in a single copy, in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate espionage attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology is now advancing like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a wired telegraph.
The (analog) videotapes had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, uncovering all the secrets of editing, while now the (digital) CDs only allow to move forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, at enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travel it entails, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary for politics and communication techniques to take us back to horse cars.
One last comment.
In the past, the press was trying to understand what was being done in secret in the embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
