For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added over three years as fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditures of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France’s aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), while purporting to respect its commitment to “new and additional” funds.
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no standard and each chooses the method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that each euro borrowed equals one euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more effective technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that is to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... At most, only the cost of the loan for the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be calculated for its commitments.
But France does not find such a reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros); see the EU document to see it for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it at 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to fulfill its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers the effort comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France makes a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending just 36.1 million euros, it manages to give the impression that it spends 420 million "new and additional", as promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why were the other member states going to continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in negotiations, since developing countries are not fools...
The early financing chapter is a minutiae, relatively short-term, in relation to the overall climate negotiations.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could move forward the debates on stakes in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter that is currently being debated): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the negotiations.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old boy ingests 81 different chemicals on a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the former movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a significant statistical value considering the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", acquired in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the food that a child about ten years old usually consumes in four meals and one snack a day.
These model meals, which respect official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three parts of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day), as well as treats, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five are classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances susceptible to act as endocrine disruptors (EP), according to studies from various institutions such as the International Center for Cancer Research.
“Although in virtually all cases the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is of concern,” the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogen residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about a dozen residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in food, in which the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian fillet, canned tuna and even bread bar or gum were dressed with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, analyses discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most “nutritive” with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk these “pollutant cocktails” generate for the consumer is “probably underestimated,” the study says.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the gravity of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase of diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
